[
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm pleased to announce that we finally have a sorry-free version of Bertrand's postulate from the 100 theorems list. Thanks to <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"117987\">@Patrick Stevens</span>  for getting this started 15 months ago and working on it with me when I came along.</p>\n<p>There is still quite a bit of golfing and cleaning up to do, but I wanted to ask a practical question: In the past I've had problems with lean timing out on some of the bounds. At this point, the file takes about a minute to become free of orange on my laptop. The most computationally intensive parts are probably the lemma currently named <code>a_584_le_exp_6</code>, which proves that <code>(584 : ℝ) ≤ exp (6.37 : ℝ)</code> by evaluating <code>norm_num</code> on the 19th degree taylor expansion of exp, and the final theorem, which does <code>norm_num</code> to verify about 10 primes, the largest of which is 1009. </p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110049\">@Mario Carneiro</span>  had suggested at one point tightening other parts of the proof to cut down on computation, but ultimately, this felt like the path of least resistance to getting a completed proof. Does taking a minute to finish compiling a file sound like too much time and strain on later CI builds/would you like me to pursue tighter bounds before trying to merge this?</p>",
        "id": 251176789,
        "sender_full_name": "Bolton Bailey",
        "timestamp": 1630291288
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Congratulations on finishing the proof! I do still think the approach is much too brute force though, and I'm also surprised that derivatives come into it, as I don't think that my metamath proof had anything like that, it was just bounds on the central binomial coefficient</p>",
        "id": 251177095,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630291654
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed, for a while we were working on <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/issues/2784\">#2784</a>, which did not use calculus, and at some point we forked that branch to this version. The derivatives are, I understand, to show that the difference in the lower and upper bound is always increasing to that when you get beyond the point where they cross, you can be sure that the theorem always holds afterwards.</p>",
        "id": 251177817,
        "sender_full_name": "Bolton Bailey",
        "timestamp": 1630292615
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Looking at my proof, I did use a bit of calculus (or rather, a theorem that would normally be proven by calculus that I did another way): log x / x is decreasing for x &gt;= e</p>",
        "id": 251178380,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630293311
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I can write up an informal summary of the proof if you don't like to read metamath, but I really think it will lead to massive proof simplification of both the computational and theoretical parts of the proof</p>",
        "id": 251178795,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630293742
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You followed this proof, right? <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Proof_of_Bertrand%27s_postulate&amp;oldid=859165151#Proof_by_Shigenori_Tochiori\">https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Proof_of_Bertrand%27s_postulate&amp;oldid=859165151#Proof_by_Shigenori_Tochiori</a></p>",
        "id": 251178921,
        "sender_full_name": "Bolton Bailey",
        "timestamp": 1630293883
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yes, with the exception that you can work out the final numeric inequality without doing that 0.97 stuff</p>",
        "id": 251178955,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630293940
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How close are you to the lemmas in that proof?</p>",
        "id": 251179008,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630293972
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>lemma 5 in particular is very easy and definitely worth it</p>",
        "id": 251179019,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630293991
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, that does seem like a big improvement, let me think about how much it would simplify Patrick's calculus proofs.</p>",
        "id": 251179150,
        "sender_full_name": "Bolton Bailey",
        "timestamp": 1630294160
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hmm, even in the Tochiori proof, you still have to prove that a linear function dominates a sqrt times a log, which is what the calculus proves.</p>",
        "id": 251179495,
        "sender_full_name": "Bolton Bailey",
        "timestamp": 1630294561
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>no, you only need the part I mentioned</p>",
        "id": 251179584,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630294651
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>log x / x is decreasing</p>",
        "id": 251179590,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630294659
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>from this you get that the function f(x) is decreasing too</p>",
        "id": 251179595,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630294667
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>which amounts to the \"linear function dominates a sqrt times a log\" fact you want</p>",
        "id": 251179656,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630294695
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but by factoring f(x) into multiples of g(x) it is much cleaner</p>",
        "id": 251179681,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630294724
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By the way, the non-calculus proof that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\log x / x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\">lo<span style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">g</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> is decreasing is this: suppose <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>e</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">e\\le x&lt;y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719400000000001em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span>, then</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mi>y</mi></mfrac><mo>&lt;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mi>x</mi></mfrac><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟺</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>y</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mi>x</mi></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟺</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mfrac><mi>y</mi><mi>x</mi></mfrac><mo>&lt;</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mfrac><mi>y</mi><mi>x</mi></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\frac{\\log y}{y}&lt;\\frac{\\log x}{x}\\iff \\log y-\\log x&lt;y\\frac{\\log x}{x}-\\log x\\iff \\log\\frac{y}{x}&lt;(\\frac{y}{x}-1)\\log x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:2.25188em;vertical-align:-0.8804400000000001em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.3714399999999998em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.314em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.677em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mop\">lo<span style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">g</span></span><span class=\"mspace