n-right:0.01389em;\">g</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≥</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> (recall <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>e</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">e\\le x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719400000000001em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>), and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\log a &lt; a-1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\">lo<span style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">g</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> follows from the identity <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&lt;</mo><msup><mi>e</mi><mi>b</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b+1&lt;e^b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68354em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.849108em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.849108em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">b</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 251180281,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630295406
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for finishing it up, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"282271\">@Bolton Bailey</span>! I did things pretty naively because I was doing it for fun :P but a meta-point is that it would be lovely if \"naive attempts just worked\": I pretty much copied the proof from my university lecture notes, and I guess an ideal world would allow a random undergrad to do that easily (even if the resulting proof shouldn't go into mathlib). In that sense, even if the entire <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/issues/8002\">#8002</a> proof is discarded, the experiment was successful in discovering and fixing a number of holes in the standard library (e.g. the fact that <code>nat.sqrt</code> didn't have an API to access it via the function <code>f x = x ^ 2</code>, the fact that <code>padic_val_nat</code>'s API was mostly not reflected down from <code>padic_val</code>, and loads of smaller random bits). The fact that Lean 4 is coming, I guess, means it isn't worth it to spend effort on optimising <code>norm_num</code> itself to make <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/issues/8002\">#8002</a> faster, but if a big migration weren't about to happen, I would definitely be giving that a go (again, even if <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/issues/8002\">#8002</a> gets completely rewritten).</p>",
        "id": 251191320,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Stevens",
        "timestamp": 1630307295
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are lots of ways to improve the proof to make brute force computation work better; for example don't call <code>norm_num</code> and use <code>norm_num1</code> instead. My opposition is only to the <em>unnecessary</em> use of brute force computation when I know there is a beautiful proof available</p>",
        "id": 251191731,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630307635
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Optimizing the lemmas for <code>norm_num</code> is also helpful; for example you should write the small primes part with a more carefully written lemma which exposes the parts that <code>norm_num</code> is supposed to do</p>",
        "id": 251191967,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630307781
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You shouldn't call tactics like <code>linarith</code> many times in a proof; the frontend has to build up a lot of state and discard it after each invocation, so it's better if you can limit the number of distinct calls and use it only when necessary</p>",
        "id": 251192113,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630307888
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's also true that it isn't worth too much to invest a lot in better brute force calculation in lean 3. Lean 4 has a fundamentally different representation of numbers that will make brute force computation much more accessible, and it would be great to have things like interval arithmetic for just plugging and chugging facts that are obvious on a graphing calculator. But that doesn't mean I won't try my darndest to keep heavy calculations out of mathlib for things that have a simple symbolic proof.</p>",
        "id": 251192910,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1630308420
    }
]